<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900615-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>900615-0016.</DOCID><HL>   SCEcorp Unit Ends   Contract for Work   On Three Power Plants</HL><DATE>06/15/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SCE CE</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   IRVINE, Calif. -- Mission Power Engineering Co., a unit ofSCEcorp., said it terminated its contract for the engineeringand construction of three geothermal power generating plantsin the Coso and China Lake areas of California, which areowned and operated by California Energy Co., San Francisco.   &quot;We've just walked off the job,&quot; said Jack Adrian, MissionPower's president and chief executive officer.</LP><TEXT>   The termination of the contract follows Mission Power'sfiling of a lawsuit on June 5 against California Energy andits partners in the $300 million-plus project. The complaint,filed in state court in Inyo County, accuses CaliforniaEnergy of making changes in the scope of the work, triggeringserious delays, and refusing to pay for additional costs.   Mission Power is seeking more than $79 million in theaction, plus interest and damages for alleged fraud andmisrepresentation by California Energy.   Michael Heys, California Energy's president, maintainedyesterday that his company has appropriately compensatedMission Power. &quot;There is nothing due on contractural work,&quot;he said. &quot;In fact, there has been an overpayment of$170,000.&quot;   Mr. Heys added that the power plants at the center of thedispute are &quot;substantially complete&quot; and, therefore, MissionPower's walkout will not cause &quot;an interruption ofoperations.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>